# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ruby
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In this guide, you will learn how controllers work and how they fit into the request cycle in your application.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Action Controller is the C in the Model View Controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] After the router has matched a controller to an incoming request, the controller is responsible for processing the request and generating the appropriate output.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] For most conventional RESTful applications, the controller will receive the request, fetch or save data from a model, and use a view to create HTML output.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You can imagine that a controller sits between models and views.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The controller makes model data available to the view, so that the view can display that data to the user.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The controller also receives user input from the view and saves or updates model data accordingly.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] A controller is a Ruby class which inherits from `ApplicationController` and has methods just like any other class.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Once an incoming request is matched to a controller by the router, Rails creates an instance of that controller class and calls the method with the same name as the action.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Given the above `ClientsController`, if a user goes to `/clients/new` in your application to add a new client, Rails will create an instance of `ClientsController` and call its `new` method.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If the `new` method is empty, Rails will automatically render the `new.html.erb` view by default.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `new` method is an instance method here, called on an instance of `ClientsController`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This should not be confused with the `new` class method (i.e., `ClientsController.new`).
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] All controllers inherit from `ApplicationController`, which in turn inherits from `ActionController::Base`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] For API only applications `ApplicationController` inherits from `ActionController::API`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Rails favors making the resource in the controller's name plural.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] For example, `ClientsController` is preferred over `ClientController` and `SiteAdminsController` over `SiteAdminController` or `SitesAdminsController`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] However, the plural names are not strictly required (e.g.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Following this naming convention will allow you to use the default route generators (e.g.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] `resources`) without needing to qualify each with options such as `:controller`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The convention also makes named route helpers consistent throughout your application.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The controller naming convention is different from models.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] While plural names are preferred for controller names, the singular form is preferred for model names (e.g.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Controller actions should be `public`, as only `public` methods are callable as actions.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] It is also best practice to lower the visibility of helper methods (with `private` or `protected`) which are *not* intended to be actions.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Some method names are reserved by Action Controller.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Accidentally redefining them could result in `SystemStackError`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If you limit your controllers to only RESTful Resource Routing actions you should not need to worry about this.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If you must use a reserved method as an action name, one workaround is to use a custom route to map the reserved method name to your non-reserved action method.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Data sent by the incoming request is available in your controller in the `params` hash.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Rails does not make a distinction between query string parameters and POST parameters; both are available in the `params` hash in your controller.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `params` hash is not a plain old Ruby Hash; instead, it is an `ActionController::Parameters` object.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] It does not inherit from Hash, but it behaves mostly like Hash.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] It provides methods for filtering `params` and, unlike a Hash, keys `:foo` and `"foo"` are considered to be the same.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `params` hash is not limited to one-dimensional keys and values.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] It can contain nested arrays and hashes.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The actual URL in this example will be encoded as `/users?ids%5b%5d=1&ids%5b%5d=2&ids%5b%5d=3` as the `[` and `]` characters are not allowed in URLs.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Most of the time you don't have to worry about this because the browser will encode it for you, and Rails will decode it automatically, but if you ever find yourself having to send those requests to the server manually you should keep this in mind.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Note that parameter values are always strings; Rails does not attempt to guess or cast the type.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Values such as `[nil]` or `[nil, nil, ...]` in `params` are replaced with `[]` for security reasons by default.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] See Security Guide for more information.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Note the nested hash in `params[:user][:address]`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `params` object acts like a Hash, but lets you use symbols and strings interchangeably as keys.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Composite key parameters contain multiple values in one parameter separated by a delimiter (e.g., an underscore).
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Therefore, you will need to extract each value so that you can pass them to Active Record.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You can use the `extract_value` method to do that.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] When a user requests the URL `/books/4_2`, the controller will extract the composite key value `["4", "2"]` and pass it to `Book.find`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `extract_value` method may be used to extract arrays out of any delimited parameters.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If your application exposes an API, you will likely accept parameters in JSON format.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If the `content-type` header of your request is set to `application/json`, Rails will automatically load your parameters into the `params` hash, which you can access as you would normally.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You can use Wrap Parameters, which automatically add the controller name to JSON parameters.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Wrap Parameters adds a clone of the parameters to the hash within a key that is the same as the controller name.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] As a result, both the original version of the parameters and the "wrapped" version of the parameters will exist in the params hash.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This feature clones and wraps parameters with a key chosen based on your controller's name.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If you do not want to wrap parameters you can configure it to `false`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You can also customize the name of the key or specific parameters you want to wrap, see the API documentation for more.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Parameters specified as part of a route declaration in the `routes.rb` file are also made available in the `params` hash.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] When a user navigates to `/clients/active` URL, `params[:status]` will be set to "active".
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] When this route is used, `params[:foo]` will also be set to "bar", as if it were passed in the query string.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Any other parameters defined by the route declaration, such as `:id`, will also be available.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In the above example, your controller will also receive `params[:action]` as "index" and `params[:controller]` as "clients".
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `params` hash will always contain the `:controller` and `:action` keys, but it's recommended to use the methods `controller_name` and `action_name` instead to access these values.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You can set global default parameters for `url_for` by defining a method called `default_url_options` in your controller.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The specified defaults will be used as a starting point when generating URLs.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] They can be overridden by the options passed to `url_for` or any path helper such as `posts_path`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Under the hood, `posts_path` is a shorthand for calling `url_for` with the appropriate parameters.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If you define `default_url_options` in `ApplicationController`, as in the example above, these defaults will be used for all URL generation.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The method can also be defined in a specific controller, in which case it only applies to URLs generated for that controller.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In a given request, the method is not actually called for every single generated URL.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] For performance reasons the returned hash is cached per request.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] With Action Controller Strong Parameters, parameters cannot be used in Active Model mass assignments until they have been explicitly permitted.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This means you will need to decide which attributes to permit for mass update and declare them in the controller.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This is a security practice to prevent users from accidentally updating sensitive model attributes.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In addition, parameters can be marked as required and the request will result in a 400 Bad Request being returned if not all required parameters are passed in.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `expect` method provides a concise and safe way to require and permit parameters.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The above `expect` will always return a scalar value and not an array or hash.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Another example is form params, you can use `expect` to ensure that the root key is present and the attributes are permitted.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In the above example, if the `:user` key is not a nested hash with the specified keys, `expect` will raise an error and return a 400 Bad Request response.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] To require and permit an entire hash of parameters, `expect` can be used in this way.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This marks the `:log_entry` parameters hash and any sub-hash of it as permitted and does not check for permitted scalars, anything is accepted.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Extreme care should be taken when calling `expect` with an empty hash, as it will allow all current and future model attributes to be mass-assigned.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] For the permitted key `:id`, its value also needs to be one of these permitted scalar values: `String`, `Symbol`, `NilClass`, `Numeric`, `TrueClass`, `FalseClass`, `Date`, `Time`, `DateTime`, `StringIO`, `IO`, `ActionDispatch::Http::UploadedFile`, and `Rack::Test::UploadedFile`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If you have not called `permit` on the key, it will be filtered out.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Arrays, hashes, or any other objects are not injected by default.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The above `permit` call ensures that values in `options` are permitted scalars and filters out anything else.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `permit` with an empty hash is convenient since sometimes it is not possible or convenient to declare each valid key of a hash parameter or its internal structure.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] But note that the above `permit` with an empty hash opens the door to arbitrary input.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] There is also `permit!` (with an `!`) which permits an entire hash of parameters without checking the values.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Extreme care should be taken when using `permit!`, as it will allow all current and *future* model attributes to be mass-assigned.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This declaration permits the `name`, `emails`, and `friends` attributes and returns them each.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] It is expected that `emails` will be an array of permitted scalar values, and that `friends` will be an array of resources (note the new double array syntax to explicitly require an array) with specific attributes.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] These attributes should have a `name` attribute (any permitted scalar values allowed), a `hobbies` attribute as an array of permitted scalar values, and a `family` attribute which is restricted to a hash with only a `name` key and any permitted scalar value.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Here are some examples of how to use `permit` for different use cases.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The concept of a cookie is not specific to Rails.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] A cookie (also known as an HTTP cookie or a web cookie) is a small piece of data from the server that is saved in the user's browser.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The browser may store cookies, create new cookies, modify existing ones, and send them back to the server with later requests.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Cookies persist data across web requests and therefore enable web applications to remember user preferences.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] To delete a cookie, you need to use `cookies.delete(:key)`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Setting the `key` to a `nil` value does not delete the cookie.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] When passed a scalar value, the cookie will be deleted when the user closes their browser.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If you want the cookie to expire at a specific time, pass a hash with the `:expires` option when setting the cookie.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If you want to create cookies that never expire use the permanent cookie jar.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This sets the assigned cookies to have an expiration date 20 years from now.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Since cookies are stored on the client browser, they can be susceptible to tampering and are not considered secure for storing sensitive data.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Rails provides a signed cookie jar and an encrypted cookie jar for storing sensitive data.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The signed cookie jar appends a cryptographic signature on the cookie values to protect their integrity.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The encrypted cookie jar encrypts the values in addition to signing them, so that they cannot be read by the user.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Refer to the API documentation for more details.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] These special cookie jars use a serializer to serialize the cookie values into strings and deserialize them into Ruby objects when read back.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You can specify which serializer to use via `config.action_dispatch.cookies_serializer`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The default serializer for new applications is `:json`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Be aware that JSON has limited support serializing Ruby objects such as `Date`, `Time`, and `Symbol`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] These will be serialized and deserialized into `String`s.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If you need to store these or more complex objects, you may need to manually convert their values when reading them in subsequent requests.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If you use the cookie session store, the above applies to the `session` and `flash` hash as well.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] While cookies are stored client-side, session data is stored server-side (in memory, a database, or a cache), and the duration is usually temporary and tied to the user's session (e.g. until they close the browser).
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] An example use case for session is storing sensitive data like user authentication.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In a Rails application, the session is available in the controller and the view.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You can use the `session` instance method to access the session in your controllers.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] To store something in the session, you can assign it to a key similar to adding a value to a hash.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] To remove something from the session, delete the key/value pair.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] It is possible to reset the entire session with `reset_session`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] It is recommended to use `reset_session` after logging in to avoid session fixation attacks.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Please refer to the Security Guide for details.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If you don't access sessions in your action's code, they will not be loaded.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Hence, you will never need to disable sessions - not accessing them will do the job.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The flash provides a way to pass temporary data between controller actions.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Anything you place in the flash will be available to the very next action and then cleared.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The flash is typically used for setting messages (e.g. notices and alerts) in a controller action before redirecting to an action that displays the message to the user.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The flash is accessed via the `flash` method.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Similar to the session, the flash values are stored as key/value pairs.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Displaying a message after a user performs some interactive action in your application is a good practice to give the user feedback that their action was successful (or that there were errors).
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In addition to `:notice`, you can also use `:alert`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] These are typically styled (using CSS) with different colors to indicate their meaning (e.g. green for notices and orange/red for alerts).
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You're not limited to `notice` and `alert`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You can set any key in a flash (similar to sessions), by assigning it to the `:flash` argument.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In the above logout example, the `destroy` action redirects to the application's `root_url`, where the message is available to be displayed.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] However, it's not displayed automatically.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] It's up to the next action to decide what, if anything, it will do with what the previous action put in the flash.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If a previous action *has* set a flash message, it's a good idea to display that to the user.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] We can accomplish this consistently by adding the HTML for displaying any flash messages in the application's default layout.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `name` above indicates the type of flash message, such as `notice` or `alert`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This information is normally used to style how the message is displayed to the user.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You can filter by `name` if you want to limit to displaying only `notice` and `alert` in layout.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Otherwise, all keys set in the `flash` will be displayed.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Including the reading and displaying of flash messages in the layout ensures that your application will display these automatically, without each view having to include logic to read the flash.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] `flash.keep` is used to carry over the flash value through to an additional request.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This is useful when there are multiple redirects.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] For example, assume that the `index` action in the controller below corresponds to the `root_url`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] And you want all requests here to be redirected to `UsersController#index`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If an action sets the flash and redirects to `MainController#index`, those flash values will be lost when another redirect happens, unless you use `flash.keep` to make the values persist for another request.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] `flash.now` is used to make the flash values available in the same request.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] By default, adding values to the flash will make them available to the next request.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] For example, if the `create` action fails to save a resource, and you render the `new` template directly, that's not going to result in a new request, but you may still want to display a message using the flash.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] All sessions have a unique ID that represents the session object; these session IDs are stored in a cookie.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] For most session stores, the unique session ID in the cookie is used to look up session data on the server (e.g. a database table).
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Rails does not allow you to pass the session ID in the URL as this is less secure.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `CookieStore` is the default and recommended session store.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] It stores all session data in the cookie itself (the session ID is still available to you if you need it).
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `CookieStore` is lightweight and does not require any configuration to use in a new application.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `CookieStore` can store 4 kB of data - much less than the other storage options - but this is usually enough.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Storing large amounts of data in the session is discouraged.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You should especially avoid storing complex objects (such as model instances) in the session.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You can use the `CacheStore` if your sessions don't store critical data or don't need to be around for long periods (for instance if you just use the flash for messaging).
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This will store sessions using the cache implementation you have configured for your application.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The advantage is that you can use your existing cache infrastructure for storing sessions without requiring any additional setup or administration.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The downside is that the session storage will be temporary and they could disappear at any time.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Read more about session storage in the Security Guide.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] There are a few configuration options related to session storage.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Rails sets up a session key (the name of the cookie) when signing the session data.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Be sure to restart your server when you modify an initializer file.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] See `config.session_store` in the configuration guide for more information.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Rails sets up a secret key for `CookieStore` used for signing the session data in `config/credentials.yml.enc`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The credentials can be updated with `bin/rails credentials:edit`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Changing the `secret_key_base` when using the `CookieStore` will invalidate all existing sessions.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You'll need to configure a cookie rotator to rotate existing sessions.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Controller callbacks are methods that are defined to automatically run before and/or after a controller action.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] A controller callback method can be defined in a given controller or in the `ApplicationController`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Since all controllers inherit from `ApplicationController`, callbacks defined here will run on every controller in your application.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Callback methods registered via `before_action` run *before* a controller action.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The method stores an error message in the flash and redirects to the login form if the user is not already logged in.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] When a `before_action` callback renders or redirects (like in the example above), the original controller action is not run.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If there are additional callbacks registered to run, they are also cancelled and not run.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In this example, the `before_action` is defined in `ApplicationController` so all controllers in the application inherit it.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] That implies that all requests in the application will require the user to be logged in.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This is fine except for the "login" page.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The "login" action should succeed even when the user is not logged in (to allow the user to log in) otherwise the user will never be able to log in.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Now, the `LoginsController`'s `new` and `create` actions will work without requiring the user to be logged in.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `:only` option skips the callback only for the listed actions; there is also an `:except` option which works the other way.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] These options can be used when registering action callbacks too, to add callbacks which only run for selected actions.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] If you register the same action callback multiple times with different options, the last action callback definition will overwrite the previous ones.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] You can also define action callbacks to run *after* a controller action has been executed with `after_action`, or to run both before and after with `around_action`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `after_action` callbacks are similar to `before_action` callbacks, but because the controller action has already been run they have access to the response data that's about to be sent to the client.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] `after_action` callbacks are executed only after a successful controller action, and not if an exception is raised in the request cycle.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `around_action` callbacks are useful when you want to execute code before and after a controller action, allowing you to encapsulate functionality that affects the action's execution.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] They are responsible for running their associated actions by yielding.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] For example, imagine you want to monitor the performance of specific actions.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Action callbacks receive `controller_name` and `action_name` as parameters you can use, as shown in the example above.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `around_action` callback also wraps rendering.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In the example above, view rendering will be included in the `duration`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The code after the `yield` in an `around_action` is run even when there is an exception in the associated action and there is an `ensure` block in the callback.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In addition to `before_action`, `after_action`, or `around_action`, there are two less common ways to register callbacks.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The first is to use a block directly with the `*_action` methods.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The block receives the controller as an argument.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Note that the action callback, in this case, uses `send` because the `logged_in?` method is private, and the action callback does not run in the scope of the controller.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This is not the recommended way to implement this particular action callback, but in simpler cases, it might be useful.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The second way is to specify a class (or any object that responds to the expected methods) for the callback action.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This can be useful in cases that are more complex.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In the above example, the `ActionDurationCallback`'s method is not run in the scope of the controller but gets `controller` as an argument.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] In general, the class being used for a `*_action` callback must implement a method with the same name as the action callback.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] So for the `before_action` callback, the class must implement a `before` method, and so on.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Also, the `around` method must `yield` to execute the action.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Every controller has two methods, `request` and `response`, which can be used to access the request and response objects associated with the current request cycle.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `request` method returns an instance of `ActionDispatch::Request`.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `response` method returns an instance of `ActionDispatch::Response`, an object representing what is going to be sent back to the client browser (e.g. from `render` or `redirect` in the controller action).
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The request object contains useful information about the request coming in from the client.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] This section describes the purpose of some of the properties of the `request` object.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] To get a full list of the available methods, refer to the Rails API documentation and Rack documentation.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Rails collects all of the parameters for a given request in the `params` hash, including the ones set in the URL as query string parameters, and those sent as the body of a `POST` request.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The request object has three methods that give you access to the various parameters.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Controllers might need to tailor a response based on context-specific information in a request.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] For example, controllers responding to requests from a mobile platform might need to render different content than requests from a desktop browser.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] One strategy to accomplish this is by customizing a request's variant.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Variant names are arbitrary, and can communicate anything from the request's platform (`:android`, `:ios`, `:linux`, `:macos`, `:windows`) to its browser (`:chrome`, `:edge`, `:firefox`, `:safari`), to the type of user (`:admin`, `:guest`, `:user`).
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The response object is built up during the execution of the action from rendering data to be sent back to the client browser.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] It's not usually used directly but sometimes, in an `after_action` callback for example, it can be useful to access the response directly.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `headers` attribute is a hash which maps header names to header values.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] Rails sets some headers automatically but if you need to update a header or add a custom header, you can use `response.headers` as in the example above.
[src:ruby/action-controller-overview] The `headers` method can be accessed directly in the controller as well.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] This guide is an introduction to Active Record.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record is part of the M in MVC - the model - which is the layer of the system responsible for representing data and business logic.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record helps you create and use Ruby objects whose attributes require persistent storage to a database.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] What is the difference between Active Record and Active Model?
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] It's possible to model data with Ruby objects that do *not* need to be backed by a database.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Model is commonly used for that in Rails, making Active Record and Active Model both part of the M in MVC, as well as your own plain Ruby objects.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] The term "Active Record" also refers to a software architecture pattern.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record in Rails is an implementation of that pattern.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] It's also a description of something called an Object Relational Mapping system.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] The Active Record pattern is described by Martin Fowler in the book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture* as "an object that wraps a row in a database table, encapsulates the database access, and adds domain logic to that data." Active Record objects carry both data and behavior.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record classes match very closely to the record structure of the underlying database.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] This way users can easily read from and write to the database, as you will see in the examples below.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Object Relational Mapping, commonly referred to as ORM, is a technique that connects the rich objects of a programming language to tables in a relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] In the case of a Rails application, these are Ruby objects.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Using an ORM, the attributes of Ruby objects, as well as the relationship between objects, can be easily stored and retrieved from a database without writing SQL statements directly.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Overall, ORMs minimize the amount of database access code you have to write.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Basic knowledge of relational database management systems (RDBMS) and structured query language (SQL) is helpful in order to fully understand Active Record.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Please refer to this SQL tutorial (or this RDBMS tutorial) or study them by other means if you would like to learn more.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] When writing applications using other programming languages or frameworks, it may be necessary to write a lot of configuration code.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] This is particularly true for ORM frameworks in general.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] However, if you follow the conventions adopted by Rails, you'll write very little to no configuration code when creating Active Record models.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Rails adopts the idea that if you configure your applications in the same way most of the time, then that way should be the default.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Explicit configuration should be needed only in those cases where you can't follow the convention.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] To take advantage of convention over configuration in Active Record, there are some naming and schema conventions to follow.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] And in case you need to, it is possible to override naming conventions.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Rails will pluralize your model's class names to find the respective database table.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] For example, a class named `Book` maps to a database table named `books`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] The Rails pluralization mechanisms are very powerful and capable of pluralizing (and singularizing) both regular and irregular words in the English language.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] This uses the Active Support pluralize method.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] For class names composed of two or more words, the model class name will follow the Ruby conventions of using an UpperCamelCase name.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] The database table name, in that case, will be a snake_case name.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record uses conventions for column names in the database tables as well, depending on the purpose of these columns.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] While these column names are optional, they are reserved by Active Record.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Steer clear of reserved keywords when naming your table's columns.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] For example, `type` is a reserved keyword used to designate a table using Single Table Inheritance (STI).
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] If you are not using STI, use a different word to accurately describe the data you are modeling.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] When generating a Rails application, an abstract `ApplicationRecord` class will be created in `app/models/application_record.rb`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] The `ApplicationRecord` class inherits from `ActiveRecord::Base` and it's what turns a regular Ruby class into an Active Record model.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] `ApplicationRecord` is the base class for all Active Record models in your app.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] This will create a `Book` model, mapped to a `books` table in the database, where each column in the table is mapped to attributes of the `Book` class.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] An instance of `Book` can represent a row in the `books` table.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] However, that is not how you do it normally in Rails.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Database tables in Rails are typically created using Active Record Migrations and not raw SQL.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] If you don't specify a type for a field (e.g., `title` instead of `title:string`), Rails will default to type `string`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] That migration creates columns `id`, `title`, `author`, `created_at` and `updated_at`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Each row of this table can be represented by an instance of the `Book` class with the same attributes: `id`, `title`, `author`, `created_at`, and `updated_at`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] You can generate the Active Record model class as well as a matching migration with the command `bin/rails generate model Book title:string author:string`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] This creates the files `app/models/book.rb`, `db/migrate/20240220143807_create_books.rb`, and a couple others for testing purposes.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record models are placed under the `app/models` directory by default.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] But you may want to organize your models by placing similar models under their own folder and namespace.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] For example, `order.rb` and `review.rb` under `app/models/book` with `Book::Order` and `Book::Review` class names, respectively.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] You can create namespaced models with Active Record.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Setting the table_name_prefix in `Book` will allow `Order` model's database table to be named `book_orders`, instead of plain `orders`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] The other possibility is that you already have a `Book` model that you want to keep in `app/models`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] In that case, you can choose `n` to not overwrite `book.rb` during the `generate` command.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] What if you need to follow a different naming convention or need to use your Rails application with a legacy database?
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] No problem, you can easily override the default conventions.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Since `ApplicationRecord` inherits from `ActiveRecord::Base`, your application's models will have a number of helpful methods available to them.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] CRUD is an acronym for the four verbs we use to operate on data: **C**reate, **R**ead, **U**pdate, and **D**elete.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record automatically creates methods to allow you to read and manipulate data stored in your application's database tables.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record makes it seamless to perform CRUD operations by using these high-level methods that abstract away database access details.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Note that all of these convenient methods result in SQL statement(s) that are executed against the underlying database.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] The examples below show a few of the CRUD methods as well as the resulting SQL statements.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record objects can be created from a hash, a block, or have their attributes manually set after creation.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] The `new` method will return a new, non-persisted object, while `create` will save the object to the database and return it.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record provides a rich API for accessing data within a database.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] You can query a single record or multiple records, filter them by any attribute, order them, group them, select specific fields, and do anything you can do with SQL.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] We can also find specific books with `find_by` and `where`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] There are many more Active Record methods to read and query records.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] You can learn more about them in the Active Record Query guide.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Once an Active Record object has been retrieved, its attributes can be modified and it can be saved to the database.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] This is useful when updating several attributes at once.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Similar to `create`, using `update` will commit the updated records to the database.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Likewise, once retrieved, an Active Record object can be destroyed, which removes it from the database.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record allows you to validate the state of a model before it gets written into the database.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] There are several methods that allow for different types of validations.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] For example, validate that an attribute value is not empty, is unique, is not already in the database, follows a specific format, and many more.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Methods like `save`, `create` and `update` validate a model before persisting it to the database.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] If the model is invalid, no database operations are performed.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] In this case the `save` and `update` methods return `false`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] The `create` method still returns the object, which can be checked for errors.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] All of these methods have a bang counterpart (that is, `save!`, `create!` and `update!`), which are stricter in that they raise an `ActiveRecord::RecordInvalid` exception when validation fails.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] The `create` method always returns the model, regardless of its validity.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] You can then inspect this model for any errors.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] You can learn more about validations in the Active Record Validations guide.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record callbacks allow you to attach code to certain events in the lifecycle of your models.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] This enables you to add behavior to your models by executing code when those events occur, like when you create a new record, update it, destroy it, and so on.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] You can learn more about callbacks in the Active Record Callbacks guide.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Rails provides a convenient way to manage changes to a database schema via migrations.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Migrations are written in a domain-specific language and stored in files which are executed against any database that Active Record supports.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Note that the above code is database-agnostic: it will run in MySQL, MariaDB, PostgreSQL, SQLite, and others.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Rails keeps track of which migrations have been committed to the database and stores them in a neighboring table in that same database called `schema_migrations`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] To run the migration and create the table, you'd run `bin/rails db:migrate`, and to roll it back and delete the table, `bin/rails db:rollback`.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] You can learn more about migrations in the Active Record Migrations guide.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Active Record associations allow you to define relationships between models.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] Associations can be used to describe one-to-one, one-to-many, and many-to-many relationships.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] The `Author` class now has methods to add and remove books to an author, and much more.
[src:ruby/active-record-basics] You can learn more about associations in the Active Record Associations guide.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] An Array object is an ordered, integer-indexed collection of objects, called *elements*; the object represents an array data structure.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] An element may be any object (even another array); elements may be any mixture of objects of different types.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] Array indexing starts at 0, as in C or Java.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] A non-negative index is *in range* if and only if it is smaller than the size of the array.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] A negative index is *in range* if and only if its absolute value is not larger than the size of the array.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] Although the effective index into an array is always an integer, some methods (both within class Array and elsewhere) accept one or more non-integer arguments that are integer-convertible objects.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] A number of Ruby methods, both in the core and in the standard library, provide instance method `to_a`, which converts an object to an array.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] In addition to the methods it mixes in through the `Enumerable` module, the `Array` class has proprietary methods for accessing, searching and otherwise manipulating arrays.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] Some of the more common ones are illustrated below.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] Elements in an array can be retrieved using the `Array#[]` method.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] It can take a single integer argument (a numeric index), a pair of arguments (start and length) or a range.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] Negative indices start counting from the end, with -1 being the last element.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] The `slice` method works in an identical manner to `Array#[]`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] To raise an error for indices outside of the array bounds or else to provide a default value when that happens, you can use `fetch`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] The special methods `first` and `last` will return the first and last elements of an array, respectively.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] Arrays keep track of their own length at all times.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] To query an array about the number of elements it contains, use `length`, `count` or `size`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] `unshift` will add a new item to the beginning of an array.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] With `insert` you can add a new element to an array at any position.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] Another common need is to remove duplicate elements from an array.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] Like all classes that include the `Enumerable` module, `Array` has an each method, which defines what elements should be iterated over and how.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] In case of Array’s `each`, all elements in the `Array` instance are yielded to the supplied block in sequence.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] Note that this operation leaves the array unchanged.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] Another sometimes useful iterator is `reverse_each` which will iterate over the elements in the array in reverse order.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] Elements can be selected from an array according to criteria defined in a block.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] The selection can happen in a destructive or a non-destructive manner.
[src:ruby/core-array-p01] While the destructive operations will modify the array they were called on, the non-destructive methods usually return a new array with the selected elements, but leave the original array unchanged.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] These methods add, replace, or reorder elements in `self`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Related: see Methods for Creating an Array.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Raises `TypeError` if the first argument is not either an array or an integer-convertible object).
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Raises `ArgumentError` if the first argument is a negative integer.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Attempts to return an array, based on the given `object`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] If `object` is an array, returns `object`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Otherwise if `object` responds to `:to_ary`. calls `object.to_ary`: if the return value is an array or `nil`, returns that value; if not, raises `TypeError`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Identifies common elements using method `#eql?` (as defined in each element of `self`).
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Element are compared using method `#eql?` (as defined in each element of `self`).
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns -1, 0, or 1 as `self` is determined to be less than, equal to, or greater than `other_array`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] This method is different from method `Array#eql?`, which compares elements using `Object#eql?`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns elements from `self`; does not modify `self`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] If `index` is out of range, returns `nil`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] If `start == self.size` and `length >= 0`, returns a new empty `Array`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Special case: If `range.start == a.size`, returns a new empty `Array`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] If `range.start` is larger than the array size, returns `nil`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] When a single `Enumerator::ArithmeticSequence` argument `aseq` is given, returns an `Array` of elements corresponding to the indexes produced by the sequence.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Unlike slicing with range, if the start or the end of the arithmetic sequence is larger than array size, throws `RangeError`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Assigns elements in `self`, based on the given `object`; returns `object`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] When `Integer` argument `index` is given, assigns `object` to an element in `self`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns whether for every element of `self`, a given criterion is satisfied.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] With both a block and argument `object` given, ignores the block and uses `object` as above.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns whether for any element of `self`, a given criterion is satisfied.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns `nil` if no such element is found.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Related: `Array#rassoc`; see also Methods for Fetching.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns the element of `self` specified by the given `index` or `nil` if there is no such element; `index` must be an integer-convertible object.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Related: `Array#[]`; see also Methods for Fetching.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns the element from `self` found by a binary search, or `nil` if the search found no suitable element.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns the integer index of the element from `self` found by a binary search, or `nil` if the search found no suitable element.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] With no block given, returns a new `Enumerator`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Related: `collect!`; see also Methods for Converting.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Related: `collect`; see also Methods for Converting.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] The order of the yielded combinations is not guaranteed.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Related: `Array#permutation`; see also Methods for Iterating.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Related: `Array#compact!`; see also Methods for Deleting.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Related: `Array#compact`; see also Methods for Deleting.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] With argument `object` and a block given, issues a warning, ignores the block, and returns the count of elements `==` to `object`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] With a block given, may call the block, depending on the value of argument `count`; `count` must be an integer-convertible object, or `nil`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Removes zero or more elements from `self`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] With a block given, removes from `self` each element `ele` such that `ele == object`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Removes the element of `self` at the given `index`, which must be an integer-convertible object.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] When `index` is out of range, returns `nil`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns a copy of `self` if no arguments are given.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Related: `Array#-`; see also Methods for Combining.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Finds and returns the object in nested object specified by `index` and `identifiers`; the nested objects may be instances of various classes.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns a new array containing all but the first `count` element of `self`, where `count` is a non-negative integer; does not modify `self`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns `true` if the count of elements in `self` is zero, `false` otherwise.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] This method is different from method `Array#==`, which compares using method `Object#==`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns the element of `self` at offset `index` if `index` is in range; `index` must be an integer-convertible object.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] With no block given, returns a new array containing the elements of `self` at the offsets specified by `indexes`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] When no block is given, raises an exception if any index is out of range.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Replaces selected elements in `self`; may add elements to `self`; always returns `self` (never a new array).
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] With a block given, calls the block with each element of `self`; removes from `self` those elements for which the block returns `false` or `nil`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns `nil` if no elements were removed.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns the zero-based integer index of a specified element, or `nil`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns `nil` if the block never returns a truthy value.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] With neither an argument nor a block given, returns a new `Enumerator`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns elements from `self`, or `nil`; does not modify `self`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns a new array that is a recursive flattening of `self` to `depth` levels of recursion; `depth` must be an integer-convertible object or `nil`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] With `nil` or negative `depth`, flattens all levels.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Related: `Array#flatten!`; see also Methods for Converting.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns `self` as a recursively flattening of `self` to `depth` levels of recursion; `depth` must be an integer-convertible object, or `nil`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns `nil` if no elements were flattened.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Related: `Array#flatten`; see also Methods for Assigning.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] No further changes may be made to `self`; raises `FrozenError` if a change is attempted.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Returns the integer hash value for `self`.
[src:ruby/core-array-p02] Inserts the given `objects` as elements of `self`; returns `self`.
