[src:ruby/core-file-p01] A File object is a representation of a file in the underlying platform.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] Class File extends module `FileTest`, supporting such singleton methods as `File.exist?`.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] Methods `File.new` and `File.open` each create a File object for a given file path.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] Note that modes `'r'` and `'r+'` are not allowed for a non-existent file (exception raised).
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] If neither is given, the stream defaults to text data.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] Note: `Method` `IO#set_encoding` does not allow the mode to be specified as an integer.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] Data mode cannot be specified as an integer.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] When the stream access mode is given as an integer, the data mode is always text, never binary.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] Note that although there is a constant `File::BINARY`, setting its value in an integer stream mode has no effect; this is because, as documented in `File::Constants`, the `File::BINARY` value disables line code conversion, but does not change the external encoding.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] When the external encoding is set, strings read are tagged by that encoding when reading, and strings written are converted to that encoding when writing.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] When both external and internal encodings are set, strings read are converted from external to internal encoding, and strings written are converted from internal to external encoding.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] For further details about transcoding input and output, see Encodings.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] If the external encoding is `'BOM|UTF-8'`, `'BOM|UTF-16LE'` or `'BOM|UTF16-BE'`, Ruby checks for a Unicode BOM in the input document to help determine the encoding.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] For UTF-16 encodings the file open mode must be binary.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] If the BOM is found, it is stripped and the external encoding from the BOM is used.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] Note that the BOM-style encoding option is case insensitive, so `'bom|utf-8'` is also valid.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] A File object has *permissions*, an octal integer representing the permissions of an actual file in the underlying platform.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] Note that file permissions are quite different from the *mode* of a file stream (File object).
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] On a Unix-based operating system, the three low-order octal digits represent the permissions for owner (6), group (4), and world (4).
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] The triplet of bits in each octal digit represent, respectively, read, write, and execute permissions.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] Permissions `0644` thus represent read-write access for owner and read-only access for group and world.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] For a directory, the meaning of the execute bit changes: when set, the directory can be searched.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] Higher-order bits in permissions may indicate the type of file (plain, directory, pipe, socket, etc.) and various other special features.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] On non-Posix operating systems, permissions may include only read-only or read-write, in which case, the remaining permission will resemble typical values.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] On Windows, for instance, the default permissions are `0644`; The only change that can be made is to make the file read-only, which is reported as `0444`.
[src:ruby/core-file-p01] Various constants for use in File and `IO` methods may be found in module `File::Constants`; an array of their names is returned by `File::Constants.constants`.
