[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] A `Hash` maps each of its unique keys to a specific value.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] You can create a `Hash` by calling method `Hash.new`.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] You can create a `Hash` by calling method `Hash.[]`.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] You can create a `Hash` by using its literal form (curly braces).
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] A `Hash` object presents its entries in the order of their creation.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] Two objects are treated as the same hash key when their `hash` value is identical and the two objects are `eql?` to each other.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] Modifying a `Hash` key while it is in use damages the hash’s index.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] To be usable as a `Hash` key, objects must implement the methods `hash` and `eql?`.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] Note: this requirement does not apply if the `Hash` uses `compare_by_identity` since comparison will then rely on the keys’ object id instead of `hash` and `eql?`.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] `Object` defines basic implementation for `hash` and `eq?` that makes each object a distinct key.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] Typically, user-defined classes will want to override these methods to provide meaningful behavior, or for example inherit `Struct` that has useful definitions for these.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] The methods `[]`, `values_at` and `dig` need to return the value associated to a certain key.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] When that key is not found, that value will be determined by its default proc (if any) or else its default (initially ‘nil`).
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] Note that the default value is used without being duplicated.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] When the default proc for a `Hash` is set (i.e., not `nil`), the default value returned by method `[]` is determined by the default proc alone.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] Note that setting the default proc will clear the default value and vice versa.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] Be aware that a default proc that modifies the hash is not thread-safe in the sense that multiple threads can call into the default proc concurrently for the same key.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] Class `Hash` also includes methods from module `Enumerable`.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] Returns a new `Hash` object populated with the given objects, if any.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] With no argument, returns a new empty `Hash`.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] When the single given argument is a `Hash`, returns a new `Hash` populated with the entries from the given `Hash`, excluding the default value or proc.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] Raises an exception if the argument list does not conform to any of the above.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] The initial default value and initial default proc for the new hash depend on which form above was used.
[src:ruby/core-hash-p01] If the optional keyword argument `capacity` is given, the hash will be allocated with enough capacity to accommodate this many keys without having to be resized.
