[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] A regular expression (also called a *regexp*) is a *match pattern* (also simply called a *pattern*).
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Note that `Regexp#match?`, `String#match?`, and `Symbol#match?` do not set global variables.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] The source literal largely behaves like a double-quoted string; see Double-Quoted String Literals.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] There are differences between an ordinary string literal and a source literal; see Shorthand Character Classes.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] When the first character of a character class is a caret (`^`), the sense of the class is inverted: it matches any character *except* those specified.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] A character class may contain another character class.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] By itself this isn’t useful because `[a-z[0-9]]` describes the same set as `[a-z0-9]`.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] However, character classes also support the `&&` operator, which performs set intersection on its arguments.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] An anchor is a metasequence that matches a zero-width position between characters in the target string.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] For a subexpression with an anchor, matching must begin at the matched anchor.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] The vertical bar metacharacter (`|`) may be used within parentheses to express alternation: two or more subexpressions any of which may match the target string.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Method `Regexp.union` provides a convenient way to construct a regexp with alternatives.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] The first capture is the entire matched string; the other captures are the matched substrings from the groups.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] A group may be made non-capturing; it is still a group (and, for example, can have a quantifier), but its matching substring is not included among the captures.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] As seen above, a capture can be referred to by its number.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Method `Regexp#named_captures` returns a hash of the capture names and substrings; method `Regexp#names` returns an array of the capture names.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] A group may be made *atomic* with `(?>`*subexpression*`)`.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] This causes the subexpression to be matched independently of the rest of the expression, so that the matched substring becomes fixed for the remainder of the match, unless the entire subexpression must be abandoned and subsequently revisited.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] In this way *subexpression* is treated as a non-divisible whole.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Atomic grouping is typically used to optimise patterns to prevent needless backtracking .
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] The next subexpression `.*` matches the next substring `Quote“` (including the trailing double-quote).
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Now there is nothing left in the target string to match the trailing subexpression `"` in the pattern; this would cause the overall match to fail.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] The matched substring is backtracked by one position: `Quote`.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] The final subexpression `"` now matches the final substring `"`, and the overall match succeeds.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Atomic grouping can affect performance; see Atomic Group.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Matches the first character in the string, `'('`.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Calls the `paren` group again, i.e. recurses back to the second step.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Matches the second character in the string, `'('`.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Attempts to call `paren` a third time, but fails because doing so would prevent an overall successful match.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Matches the fourth character in the string, `')'`.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] The absence operator is a special group that matches anything which does *not* match the contained subexpressions.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] See Unicode Properties for regexps based on the numerous properties.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Below are the Unicode character category abbreviations and names.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Enumerations of characters in each category are at the links.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] A POSIX *bracket expression* is also similar to a character class.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] The comment may not include an unescaped terminator character.
