[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Method `Regexp#options` returns an integer whose value showing the settings for case-insensitivity mode, multiline mode, and extended mode.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Method `Regexp#casefold?` returns whether the mode is case-insensitive.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Unlike other languages, the modifier `m` does not affect the anchors `^` and `$`.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] These anchors always match at line-boundaries in Ruby.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] In extended mode, whitespace and comments may be used to form a self-documented regexp.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Modifier `o` means that the first time a literal regexp with interpolations is encountered, the generated `Regexp` object is saved and used for all future evaluations of that literal regexp.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Without modifier `o`, the generated `Regexp` is not saved, so each evaluation of the literal regexp generates a new `Regexp` object.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Note that if the literal regexp does not have interpolations, the `o` behavior is the default.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] A regular expression containing non-US-ASCII characters is assumed to use the source encoding.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] This can be overridden with one of the following modifiers.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] If a match between incompatible encodings is attempted an `Encoding::CompatibilityError` exception is raised.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] When either a regexp source or a target string comes from untrusted input, malicious values could become a denial-of-service attack; to prevent such an attack, it is wise to set a timeout.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] For certain values of the pattern and target string, matching time can grow polynomially or exponentially in relation to the input size; the potential vulnerability arising from this is the regular expression denial-of-service (ReDoS) attack.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] Regexp matching can apply an optimization to prevent ReDoS attacks.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] When the optimization is applied, matching time increases linearly (not polynomially or exponentially) in relation to the input size, and a ReDoS attach is not possible.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p01] However, an untrusted source may not be safe even if the method returns `true`, because the optimization uses memoization (which may invoke large memory consumption).
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p02] Returns `true` if matching against `re` can be done in linear time to the input string.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p02] Note that this is a property of the ruby interpreter, not of the argument regular expression.
[src:ruby/core-regexp-p02] Identical regexp can or cannot run in linear time depending on your ruby binary.
