[src:ruby/core-string-p01] A `String` object has an arbitrary sequence of bytes, typically representing text or binary data.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] A `String` object may be created using `String::new` or as literals.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] `String` objects differ from `Symbol` objects in that `Symbol` objects are designed to be used as identifiers, instead of text or data.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] Typically, a method whose name ends with `!` modifies `self` and returns `self`; often, a similarly named method (without the `!`) returns a new string.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] In general, if both bang and non-bang versions of a method exist, the bang method mutates and the non-bang method does not.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] However, a method without a bang can also mutate, such as `String#replace`.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] The examples in this section mostly use the `String#sub` and `String#gsub` methods; the principles illustrated apply to all four substitution methods.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] If `replacement` is a string, that string determines the replacing string that is substituted for the matched text.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] Each of the examples above uses a simple string as the replacing string.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] Note that within the string `replacement`, a character combination such as `$&` is treated as ordinary text, not as a special match variable.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] Note that `\\` is interpreted as an escape, i.e., a single backslash.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] Note also that a string literal consumes backslashes.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] See String Literals for details about string literals.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] A back-reference is typically preceded by an additional backslash.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] For example, if you want to write a back-reference `\&` in `replacement` with a double-quoted string literal, you need to write `"..\\&.."`.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] If you want to write a non-back-reference string `\&` in `replacement`, you need to first escape the backslash to prevent this method from interpreting it as a back-reference, and then you need to escape the backslashes again to prevent a string literal from consuming them: `"..\\\\&.."`.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] You may want to use the block form to avoid excessive backslashes.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] Special match variables such as `$1`, `$2`, $`, `$&`, and `$'` are set appropriately.
[src:ruby/core-string-p01] A *slice* of a string is a substring selected by certain criteria.
