[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] Returns the index of the first element that meets a specified criterion, or `nil` if no such element is found.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] With no argument and no block given, returns an `Enumerator`.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] Returns an array of objects based elements of `self` that match the given pattern.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] Returns an array of objects based on elements of `self` that *don’t* match the given pattern.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] Returns the result of applying a reducer to an initial value and the first element of the `Enumerable`.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] It then takes the result and applies the function to it and the second element of the collection, and so on.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] The return value is the result returned by the final call to the function.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] In a way the `inject` function *injects* the function between the elements of the enumerable.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] You use it when you want to *reduce* a collection to a single value.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] When this runs, the block is first called with `1` (the initial value) and `2` (the first element of the array).
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] The block returns `1*2`, so on the next iteration the block is called with `2` (the previous result) and `3`.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] The block returns `6`, and is called one last time with `6` and `4`.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] The result of the block, `24` becomes the value returned by `inject`.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] This code returns the product of the elements in the enumerable.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] In the case of the previous example, the initial value, `1`, wasn’t really necessary: the calculation of the product of a list of numbers is self-contained.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] In these circumstances, you can omit the `initial_value` parameter.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] `inject` will then initially call the block with the first element of the collection as the `result` parameter and the second element as the `next_value`.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] This shortcut is convenient, but can only be used when the block produces a result which can be passed back to it as a first parameter.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] Here’s an example where that’s not the case: it returns a hash where the keys are words and the values are the number of occurrences of that word in the enumerable.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] Note that the last line of the block is just the word `counts`.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] This ensures the return value of the block is the result that’s being calculated.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] A *reducer function* is a function that takes a partial result and the next value, returning the next partial result.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] The block that is given to `inject` is a reducer.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] You can also write a reducer as a function and pass the name of that function (as a symbol) to `inject`.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] Must return an updated result which will also implement the function.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] Here’s an example that adds elements to a string.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] The two calls invoke the functions `String#concat` and `String#+` on the result so far, passing it the next value.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] Here’s a more complex example when the result object maintains state of a different type to the enumerable elements.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] If your reducer returns a value that it can accept as a parameter, then you don’t have to pass in an initial value.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] And an example that converts a hash to an array of two-element subarrays.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] Returns an `Enumerator::Lazy`, which redefines most `Enumerable` methods to postpone enumeration and enumerate values only on an as-needed basis.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] Returns the element with the maximum element according to a given criterion.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] The ordering of equal elements is indeterminate and may be unstable.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p02] With a block given, the block determines the maximum elements.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] With a block given and positive integer argument `n` given, returns an array containing the first `n` maximum elements that exist, as determined by the block.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Returns the elements for which the block returns the maximum values.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Returns an `Enumerator` if no block is given.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Returns the element with the minimum element according to a given criterion.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] With a block given, the block determines the minimum elements.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] With a block given and positive integer argument `n` given, returns an array containing the first `n` minimum elements that exist, as determined by the block.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Returns the elements for which the block returns the minimum values.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Returns a 2-element array containing the minimum and maximum elements according to a given criterion.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Returns whether no element meets a given criterion.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Returns whether exactly one element meets a given criterion.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Returns an array of objects rejected by the block.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] The ends of chunks are defined by *pattern* and the block.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] If `*pattern* === *elt*` returns `true` or the block returns `true` for the element, the element is end of a chunk.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] The `===` and *block* is called from the first element to the last element of *enum*.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Other methods of the `Enumerator` class and `Enumerable` module, such as `map`, etc., are also usable.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] With argument `pattern`, returns an enumerator that uses the pattern to partition elements into arrays (“slices”).
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] An element begins a new slice if `element === pattern` (or if it is the first element).
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] With a block, returns an enumerator that uses the block to partition elements into arrays.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] “svn proplist -R” produces multiline output for each file.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] If the block needs to maintain state over multiple elements, local variables can be used.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] However local variables should be used carefully if the result enumerator is enumerated twice or more.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] The local variables should be initialized for each enumeration.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] mbox contains series of mails which start with Unix From line.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] So each mail can be extracted by slice before Unix From line.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] This method split chunks between *elt_before* and *elt_after* where the block returns `true`.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] `Enumerable#chunk_while` does the same, except splitting when the block returns `false` instead of `true`.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Returns an array containing the sorted elements of `self`.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] With a block given, comparisons in the block determine the ordering.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] It implements a Schwartzian transform which is useful when key computation or comparison is expensive.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] With a block given, returns an array of elements of `self`, sorted according to the value returned by the block for each element.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] The current implementation of `sort_by` generates an array of tuples containing the original collection element and the mapped value.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] This makes `sort_by` fairly expensive when the keysets are simple.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] However, consider the case where comparing the keys is a non-trivial operation.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] The following code sorts some files on modification time using the basic `sort` method.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] This sort is inefficient: it generates two new `File` objects during every comparison.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] A slightly better technique is to use the `Kernel#test` method to generate the modification times directly.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] This still generates many unnecessary `Time` objects.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] A more efficient technique is to cache the sort keys (modification times in this case) before the sort.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Perl users often call this approach a Schwartzian transform, after Randal Schwartz.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] We construct a temporary array, where each element is an array containing our sort key along with the filename.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] We sort this array, and then extract the filename from the result.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] This is exactly what `sort_by` does internally.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Generally, the sum is computed using methods `+` and `each`; for performance optimizations, those methods may not be used, and so any redefinition of those methods may not have effect here.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] The key to be added or found for an element depends on the class of `self`; see Enumerable in Ruby Classes.
[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] Raises an exception if an element of `self` is not a 2-element array, and a block is not passed.
