[src:ruby/enumerable-p03] With no block given, returns a new array `new_array` of size self.size whose elements are arrays.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This guide covers getting up and running with Ruby on Rails.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] In this guide, we'll walk through the core concepts of building web applications with Rails.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] You don't need any experience with Rails to follow along with this guide.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails is a web framework built for the Ruby programming language.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails takes advantage of many features of Ruby so we **strongly** recommend learning the basics of Ruby so that you understand some of the basic terms and vocabulary you will see in this tutorial.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails is a web application development framework written in the Ruby programming language.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] It is designed to make programming web applications easier by making assumptions about what every developer needs to get started.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] It allows you to write less code while accomplishing more than many other languages and frameworks.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Experienced Rails developers also report that it makes web application development more fun.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] It makes the assumption that there is a "best" way to do things, and it's designed to encourage that way - and in some cases to discourage alternatives.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] If you learn "The Rails Way" you'll probably discover a tremendous increase in productivity.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] If you persist in bringing old habits from other languages to your Rails development, and trying to use patterns you learned elsewhere, you may have a less happy experience.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] We're going to build a project called `store` - a simple e-commerce app that demonstrates several of Rails' built-in features.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Any commands prefaced with a dollar sign `$` should be run in the terminal.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Follow the Install Ruby on Rails Guide if you need to install Ruby and/or Rails.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Let's verify the correct version of Rails is installed.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] To display the current version, open a terminal and run the following.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] The version shown should be Rails 8.1.0 or higher.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails comes with several commands to make life easier.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Run `rails --help` to see all of the commands.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] `rails new` generates the foundation of a fresh Rails application for you, so let's start there.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] You can customize the application Rails generates by using flags.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] To see these options, run `rails new --help`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Let's take a quick glance at the files and directories that are included in a new Rails application.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] You can open this folder in your code editor or run `ls -la` in your terminal to see the files and directories.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails code is organized using the Model-View-Controller (MVC) architecture.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Now that we've got a basic understanding of MVC, let's see how it's used in Rails.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Let's start easy by creating our application's database and boot up our Rails server for the first time.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This will initially create the application's database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] When we run commands inside an application directory, we should use `bin/rails`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This makes sure the application's version of Rails is used.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] To see your Rails application, open http://localhost:3000 in your browser.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This page is the *smoke test* for a new Rails application, ensuring that everything is working behind the scenes to serve a page.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] To stop the Rails server anytime, press `Ctrl-C` in your terminal.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Developer happiness is a cornerstone philosophy of Rails and one way of achieving this is with automatic code reloading in development.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Once you start the Rails server, new files or changes to existing files are detected and automatically loaded or reloaded as necessary.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This allows you to focus on building without having to restart your Rails server after every change.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] You may also notice that Rails applications rarely use `require` statements like you may have seen in other programming languages.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails uses naming conventions to require files automatically so you can focus on writing your application code.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] See Autoloading and Reloading Constants for more details.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Active Record is a feature of Rails that maps relational databases to Ruby code.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] It helps generate the structured query language (SQL) for interacting with the database like creating, updating, and deleting tables and records.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Our application is using SQLite which is the default for Rails.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Let's start by adding a database table to our Rails application to add products to our simple e-commerce store.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This command tells Rails to generate a model named `Product` which has a `name` column and type of `string` in the database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Later on, you'll learn how to add other column types.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] An Active Record model in `app/models/product.rb`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Model names are *singular*, because an instantiated model represents a single record in the database (i.e., You are creating a *product* to add to the database.).
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] A *migration* is a set of changes we want to make to our database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] By defining migrations, we're telling Rails how to change the database to add, change, or remove tables, columns or other attributes of our database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This helps keep track of changes we make in development (only on our computer) so they can be deployed to production (live, online!) safely.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] In your code editor, open the migration Rails created for us so we can see what the migration does.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This migration is telling Rails to create a new database table named `products`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] In contrast to the model above, Rails makes the database table names *plural*, because the database holds all of the instances of each model (i.e., You are creating a database of *products*).
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] The `create_table` block then defines which columns and types should be defined in this database table.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] `t.string :name` tells Rails to create a column in the `products` table called `name` and set the type as `string`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] `t.timestamps` is a shortcut for defining two columns on your models: `created_at:datetime` and `updated_at:datetime`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] You'll see these columns on most Active Record models in Rails and they are automatically set by Active Record when creating or updating records.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This command checks for any new migrations and applies them to your database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] If you make a mistake, you can run `bin/rails db:rollback` to undo the last migration.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Now that we have created our products table, we can interact with it in Rails.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] For this, we're going to use a Rails feature called the *console*.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] The console is a helpful, interactive tool for testing our code in our Rails application.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Here we can type code that will be executed when we hit `Enter`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] When we ran the Rails model generator to create the `Product` model, it created a file at `app/models/product.rb`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This file creates a class that uses Active Record for interacting with our `products` database table.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] You might be surprised that there is no code in this class.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] How does Rails know what defines this model?
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] When the `Product` model is used, Rails will query the database table for the column names and types and automatically generate code for these attributes.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails saves us from writing this boilerplate code and instead takes care of it for us behind the scenes so we can focus on our application logic instead.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Let's use the Rails console to see what columns Rails detects for the Product model.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails asked the database for column information above and used that information to define attributes on the `Product` class dynamically so you don't have to manually define each of them.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This is one example of how Rails makes development a breeze.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] The `product` variable is an instance of `Product`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] It has not been saved to the database, and so does not have an ID, created_at, or updated_at timestamps.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] We can call `save` to write the record to the database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] When `save` is called, Rails takes the attributes in memory and generates an `INSERT` SQL query to insert this record into the database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails also updates the object in memory with the database record `id` along with the `created_at` and `updated_at` timestamps.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] We can see that by printing out the `product` variable.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Similar to `save`, we can use `create` to instantiate and save an Active Record object in a single call.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] We can also look up records from the database using our Active Record model.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] To find all the Product records in the database, we can use the `all` method.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This is a *class* method, which is why we can use it on Product (versus an instance method that we would call on the product instance, like `save` above).
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This generates a `SELECT` SQL query to load all records from the `products` table.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Each record is automatically converted into an instance of our Product Active Record model so we can easily work with them from Ruby.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] The `all` method returns an `ActiveRecord::Relation` object which is an Array-like collection of database records with features to filter, sort, and execute other database operations.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] What if we want to filter the results from our database?
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] We can use `where` to filter records by a column.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This generates a `SELECT` SQL query but also adds a `WHERE` clause to filter the records that have a `name` matching `"Pants"`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This also returns an `ActiveRecord::Relation` because multiple records may have the same name.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] We can use `order(name: :asc)` to sort records by name in ascending alphabetical order.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] What if we want to find one specific record?
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] We can do this by using the `find` class method to look up a single record by ID.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This generates a `SELECT` query but specifies a `WHERE` for the `id` column matching the ID of `1` that was passed in.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] It also adds a `LIMIT` to only return a single record.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This time, we get a `Product` instance instead of an `ActiveRecord::Relation` since we're only retrieving a single record from the database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Records can be updated in 2 ways: using `update` or assigning attributes and calling `save`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] We can call `update` on a Product instance and pass in a Hash of new attributes to save to the database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This will assign the attributes, run validations, and save the changes to the database in one method call.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This updated the name of the "T-Shirt" product to "Shoes" in the database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Confirm this by running `Product.all` again.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] You will see two products: Shoes and Pants.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Alternatively, we can assign attributes and call `save` when we're ready to validate and save changes to the database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Let's change the name "Shoes" back to "T-Shirt".
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] The `destroy` method can be used to delete a record from the database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This deleted the T-Shirt product from our database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] We can confirm this with `Product.all` to see that it only returns Pants.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Active Record provides *validations* which allows you to ensure data inserted into the database adheres to certain rules.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Let's add a `presence` validation to the Product model to ensure that all products must have a `name`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] You might remember that Rails automatically reloads changes during development.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] However, if the console is running when you make updates to the code, you'll need to manually refresh it.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] So let's do this now by running 'reload!'.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Let's try to create a Product without a name in the Rails console.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This time `save` returns `false` because the `name` attribute wasn't specified.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails automatically runs validations during create, update, and save operations to ensure valid input.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] To see a list of errors generated by validations, we can call `errors` on the instance.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This returns an `ActiveModel::Errors` object that can tell us exactly which errors are present.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] It also can generate friendly error messages for us that we can use in our user interface.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Now let's build a web interface for our Products.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] We are done with the console for now, so you can exit out of it by running `exit`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] To get Rails saying "Hello", you need to create at minimum a *route*, a *controller* with an *action*, and a *view*.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] A route maps a request to a controller action.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] A controller action performs the necessary work to handle the request, and prepares any data for the view.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] A view displays data in a desired format.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] In terms of implementation: Routes are rules written in a Ruby DSL (Domain-Specific Language).
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Controllers are Ruby classes, and their public methods are actions.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] And views are templates, usually written in a mixture of HTML and Ruby.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] That's the short of it, but we’re going to walk through each of these steps in more detail next.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] In Rails, a route is the part of the URL that determines how an incoming HTTP request is directed to the appropriate controller and action for processing.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] First, let's do a quick refresher on URLs and HTTP Request methods.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] HTTP requests use methods to tell a server what action it should perform for a given URL.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] A `route` in Rails refers to a line of code that pairs an HTTP Method and a URL path.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] The route also tells Rails which `controller` and `action` should respond to a request.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This route tells Rails to look for GET requests to the `/products` path.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] In this example, we specified `"products#index"` for where to route the request.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] When Rails sees a request that matches, it will send the request to the `ProductsController` and the `index` action inside of that controller.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This is how Rails will process the request and return a response to the browser.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] You'll notice that we don't need to specify the protocol, domain, or query params in our routes.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] That's basically because the protocol and domain make sure the request reaches your server.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] From there, Rails picks up the request and knows which path to use for responding to the request based on what routes are defined.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] The query params are like options that Rails can use to apply to the request, so they are typically used in the controller for filtering the data.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Here, we've told Rails to take POST requests to "/products" and process them with the `ProductsController` using the `create` action.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Routes may also need to match URLs with certain patterns.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] This is called a `parameter` and it captures a portion of the URL to be used later for processing the request.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] If a user visits `/products/1`, the `:id` param is set to `1` and can be used in the controller action to look up and display the Product record with an ID of 1.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] `/products/2` would display Product with an ID of 2 and so on.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Route parameters don't have to be Integers, either.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails will capture `hello-world` out of `/blog/hello-world` and this can be used to look up the blog post with the matching title.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] There are 4 common actions you will generally need for a resource: Create, Read, Update, Delete (CRUD).
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Typing out these routes every time is redundant, so Rails provides a shortcut for defining them.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] If you don’t want all these CRUD actions, you specify exactly what you need.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Check out the routing guide for details.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] Rails provides a command that displays all the routes your application responds to.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] In your terminal, run the following command.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p01] You'll also see routes from other built-in Rails features like health checks.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] Now that we've defined routes for Products, let's implement the controller and actions to handle requests to these URLs.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] This command will generate a `ProductsController` with an index action.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] Since we've already set up routes, we can skip that part of the generator using a flag.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] Let's take a look at the ProductsController defined in `app/controllers/products_controller.rb`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] You may notice the file name `products_controller.rb` is an underscored version of the Class this file defines, `ProductsController`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] This pattern helps Rails to automatically load code without having to use `require` like you may have seen in other languages.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] Even though it's an empty method, Rails will default to rendering a template with the matching name.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] The `index` action will render `app/views/products/index.html.erb`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] If we open up that file in our code editor, we'll see the HTML it renders.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] First, run `bin/rails server` in your terminal to start the Rails server.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] Then open http://localhost:3000 and you will see the Rails welcome page.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] If we open http://localhost:3000/products in the browser, Rails will render the products index HTML.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] Our browser requested `/products` and Rails matched this route to `products#index`.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] Rails sent the request to the `ProductsController` and called the `index` action.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] Since this action was empty, Rails rendered the matching template at `app/views/products/index.html.erb` and returned that to our browser.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] Now when you visit http://localhost:3000, Rails will render Products#index.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] Let's take this a step further and render some records from our database.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] In the `index` action, let's add a database query and assign it to an instance variable.
[src:ruby/getting-started-p02] Rails uses instance variables (variables that start with an @) to share data with the views.
